	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Jun 11th 6:01 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Keeping your weapon skills up isn't essential (atleast if your grouping predominatly), but you WILL want to keep defense and dodge maxed every chance you get. Even with a tank taunting and attacking for all he's worth we still need time to get the things attention - especially if the mages just dropped a tactical nuke on it and its looking for revenge. Having maxed defense and dodge skill might let you avoid one more hit and live, which is one more round for the tank to get the things attention.<br><br>Now if your soloing in an area with lots of aggressive yard trash (example - Warslilks Woods with its goblins & decayinging skeletons) you might want to pack a good weapon and be adept with it. I've seen a few weaponless casters that tried to meditate while the pets fighting a giant and suddenly got attacked by some newbie critter. The mage either had to use his hard-gotten mana to fry the critter with a spell suited for much bigger prey so he could meditate (again), try to take it in hand-to-hand (sans main hand item), or in the worst (but most amusing) case - watching the 29th mage run for the zone with a decaying skeleton in tow when the giant starts winning against the pet.<br><br>Now I am NOT suggesting that you melee on a regular basis when there is a tank in the group. In fact I suggest that when you are grouped DO NOT attack the critter in melee unless you have full mana, its running away, and its been snared. If its still fighting or moving away at speed you are a much bigger help dropping some direct damage to put it down.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
