<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99074440454420></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99074440454420><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=99074440454420>Pet Strats</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=99074440454420#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, May 24th 6:46 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I want to dispel some really prolific misinformation about Mage's pets and confirm some other points.<br><br>1. The beloved earth pet - the truth is that he BLOWS!&nbsp;&nbsp;You heard that right, the earth pet sux.  I know this is major heresy to conventional wisdom, but let me explain why the earth pet is actually the worst of all pets.  Sure, the EP(earth pet) has the most hp, but his agility is so bad that mobs just eat through all those extra hps.  Now you are stuck wasting time regenerating those same extra hps just to get going again.  The root sux, as it is often resisted, does no damage til very late levels.  Worst of all, the root forces a mob to continue trading blows with the EP instead of turning its back on you to run away.  Once the mob turns its back, damaging it enough to slow it down (to prevent adds) is easy.  If the mob is running toward another mob, nuke him, otherwise the pet will take him down, with no additional damage to itself.  To boot, the EP does not do as much damage as a FP(fire pet) and only *slightly* out damages a WP(water pet).  EPs are especially worthless in groups, as most pets are ignored by mobs when there are any kind of melee'ers in the group and someone else always seems to be rooting/snaring with better success.  I think people were hung up on the EP because they figured 'most hp + strength = best pet', but I can't tell you how many earth pets I have lost because a mob would continue to fight it instead of turning its back to run.  I understand people like there mobs rooted, but it isn't all that necessary if you moderate nuking with your pet's taunt.  In conclusion - Use  EP only when soloing in a dangerous zone where you really cant afford to have the mob run off to get adds.<br><br>2. The water pet - is likely the best pet in the game.  It is my favorite, especially when soloing.  It has good agility and therefore gets hit less, and thus takes less damage than a EP.  Has good strength, ac and hp plus has a small water/ice nuke which adds to the overall damage and strikes down fleeing mobs.  It is also immune to poison. Best of all, its regen rate is the fastest.  Which gets you back in the business hunting quicker.  If a mob misses an couple shots, these guys will actually heal about 1% in the middle of a battle  =).  Put a damage shield on one of these, and you'll have a watery juggernaut.  I will often just sit and med through a low blue mob with these guys.  Conclusion - the best for soloing.<br><br>3. The air pet - can be summed up in one word, "stun".  It's not a bad pet if you can get past the low hp and ac and the lowest damage.  The AP(air pet) really shines when it stuns a mob.  After all, a stunned mob cant deal out any hits.  For this reason the AP is especially good against casters which can't melee for much anyway, but the stun ruins spells.   When the mob is not stunned the AP still manages to survive do to its high agility.  The other major feature of the AP is its invisibility.  This makes it good for use in dungeons where the stupid pet's waypoint system will drag it all over the zone trying to catch up with you, dragging every mob in the zone with it.  Someone had posted this little pearl of wisdom on a message board somewhere:"There is nothing more frightening to a mage, than to be in the middle of the zone when you see the 'Taunting Attack' message, but your pet is nowhere to be seen"  Had that happen to me in Unrest.  Next thing I knew a Festering Hag had nuked me for 80% of my life.  An AP might have prevented that.  Conclusion - Use in dungeons or zones where way-pointing is a problem, and against casters.<br><br>4. The misunderstood fire pet - he not an evil guy...just misunderstood.  I actually rate the fire pet second best &lt;&lt;dozens of jaws drop to the floor&gt;&gt; of the pets.  It is true that the FP's hit points suck a big bowl of a$$, but the FP's offensive qualities will keep the mob's hp just as low.  Casting damage shields on the other pets _every fight_ is very mana consuming, mana better spent nuking.  But a FP *always* has a damage shield on, and it is better than yours.  Low blues will often take more damage off the shield than they can dish out to the pet  Plus the FP has the hardest hit of the pets.  All this combined with a nuke or two your own will cut down mobs fast (thus allow for faster leveling).  The fire pets disadvantages make it dangerous with more than one mob as you can only safely nuke one mob at a time.  FPs are hands down the best grouping pets.  In a group the top melee guy will attract most of the attention, so my pets are rarely even swung at and return with 100% hp 9 times out of 10.  Therefore, hp are not an issue, go for pure offense(unless the pet IS the tank of course).  FPs do require the most management because there hp are so low, so newbie mages may want to stick with a more robust pet.  Conclusion - group with this pet, soloing is possible, but watch the hp.<br><br><br>You may not agree with me, but don't listen to all the 'EP is the best, FP is the worst' nonsense that keeps getting recycled to all the newbies.  Try'em for yourself at different points and zones in the game.  They all the best at certain points, in certain zones.<br>Well I guess I will just wait for the flames to come in now, happy hunting.<br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
